<DOC><DOCNO> AP890518-0200 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-89 2036EST</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     05-18 0595</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0612</SECOND><HEAD>Severe Weather Over The Central Gulf Coast And The Plains</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Severe thunderstorms battered Louisiana and southeastern Texason Thursday, producing tornadoes, damaging wind and very heavy rainfor a second day in a row, and thunderstorms also developed overthe Plains.   From 5 to 14 inches of rain fell in 24 hours over southeasternTexas and western Louisiana. Coushatta, La., reported 14.20 inchesin 24 hours.   Flooding closed some 40 major roads in Louisiana, State Policesaid.   Two train engines and 15 rail cars derailed during the nightwhen they hit flooded tracks in northwestern Louisiana's Red RiverParish, authorities said Thursday.   A tornado was reported near Rayne, La., in Acadia Parish shortlybefore noon and another was spotted northeast of Lafayette, La.,after noon, authorities. There were no immediate reports ofinjuries.   A tornado also was reported briefly on the ground near downtownHouston, Texas.   On Wednesday, a tornado killed a woman and four people drownedin swollen creeks in Texas. Flooding forced hundreds of Dallas-FortWorth area residents to leave their homes. A levee failed along theTrinity River in Dallas and rising tributaries forced moreevacuations Thursday.   In Lake Charles, La., the roof of a building housing a Masoniclodge and a furniture store collapsed early Thursday under theweight of collected rain water, said Civil Defense director JerryMerchant. There were no injuries.   Wind damage was reported elsewhere in Louisiana with power linesdown and trees blown onto at least two mobile homes, the NationalWeather Service said.   Heavier rain during the six hours up to 1 p.m. CDT included 5.11inches at Houston's airport; 3.23 inches at Beaumont-Port Arthur,Texas; and 2.50 inches at Lake Charles, La.   Another area of severe thunderstorms developed across easternKansas and eastern Oklahoma. Tornadoes were reported in Kansas nearSylvia and Clay Center and in northeastern Oklahoma's Wagoner andRogers counties, the weather service said.   Two houses and two mobile homes were damaged by the Oklahomatwisters and one person was injured, authorities said.   Gerald Gouard, Rogers County, Okla., commissioner, saidrelatives who gathered at his house before a funeral saw onetornado develop. The tornado came to the edge of his yard, but roseup over the house and a shop before hitting another house.   Hail as big as golf balls fell west of Valley Falls, Kan., andhail an inch in diameter fell elsewhere in Kansas at Basehor,Linwood and Kansas City.   Overbrook, Kan., got half an inch of rain in 10 minutes.   Elsewhere, rain was scattered over the northern Pacific Coast,as well as from south-central Nebraska into northern Illinois. Asnow advisory was posted for the Cascades of Oregon.   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 32degrees at Butte, Mont., to 97 at Beeville, Texas. Thursday's lowfor the 48 contiguous states was 23 degrees at Gunnison, Colo.   For Friday, showers and thunderstorms were forecast from thecentral and eastern Gulf Coast region across much of theMississippi Valley, and the Ohio Valley into the upper Great Lakes.Showers and some thunderstorms were expected over the northernPlains. Showers were forecast across the Pacific Northwest.   Highs in the 50s and 60s were predicted from the northern andcentral Pacific Coast to the upper Missouri Valley; in the 60sacross northeastern Minnesota and much of Wisconsin; in the 90sacross much of Texas, the southern Rockies, the desert Southwestand the central and southern Florida Peninsula; and generally inthe 70s or 80s in the remainder of the nation.</TEXT></DOC>